			<ns0:name>pa...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/101628056640429344673/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">The current validator allows adding REX prefix to all valid instructions. However, there are some instructions that ignore this prefix (example: CALL, JMP, LOOP, PUSH imm32, ...).

The AMD manual lists the specific instructions that ignore REX, the Intel manual says: &amp;quot;A prefix is necessary only if an instruction references one of the extended registers or uses a 64-bit operand. If a REX prefix is used when it has no meaning, it is ignored.&amp;quot;

Such sequences look redundant, since compilers would not generate them. It would be cleaner to disallow this &amp;quot;ignored REX&amp;quot;.

It would be ideal to fix it in the old validator, but if it turns out to be hard, we can approach this from the validator_ragel to make it equivalent for some time during review, them roll back to what it is now (i.e. not accepting meaningless prefixes). Will see.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2012-08-23T20:59:56.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2012-03-19T17:16:34.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>Fixed</ns2:status><ns2:owner>
